<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Sierra Leone </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Team Arrives To Train National Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Team Arrives To Train National Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1205130994 Lagos Radio Nigeria Network in English 2100 GMT 
11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1205130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Lagos Radio Nigeria Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A team of Nigerian military personnel has arrived in 
Freetown to train and reorganize the Sierra Leonean Armed 
Forces. The 32-member team is led by Brigadier General (Seidu 
Zubiru). 
  Addressing newsmen in Lagos, the director of defense 
information, Brigadier General Fred Chijuka, said the team will 
be in Sierra Leone for an initial period of two years. He said 
the exercise was at the instance of Sierra Leone Government, 
adding that more African countries were also requesting similar 
military assistance from Nigeria. 
  Meanwhile, about 200 Nigerians residing in Sierra Leone were 
flown into Lagos last night, in a Nigerian Air Force plane, 
following renewed fighting by government and rebel forces in 
that country. They are mainly children and women. A radio 
Nigeria correspondent reports that some of them came with little 
or no luggage, saying that they had been dispossessed of their 
belongings. 

</TEXT>

