<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Niger </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civil Servants Strike, Demand Salary Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Civil Servants Strike, Demand Salary Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1705183194 Paris AFP in French 0923 GMT 17 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1705183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Niamey, 17 May (AFP) -- The 40,000 Niger civil 
servants today resumed their strike, which will last four days 
this time, in order to obtain a 30- to 50-percent salary 
increase to compensate for the reduction in their purchasing 
power following the CFA franc devaluation. 
  The workers are also demanding the abrogation of a law 
adopted by the National Assembly regulating the right to strike. 
Civil servants have already launched two strikes, from 12 to 14 
April, and from 10 to 12 May for the same reasons. On 16 April, 
government authorities decided on a 5- to 12-percent increase, 
adding that they would not offer any more. 
  "Workers are determined to multiply strikes to obtain 
complete satisfaction for their demands," Ibrahim Mayaki, the 
secretary general of the Federation of Labor Unions of Niger. 
  Despite troubles due to sporadic power cuts, banks and 
business were operating normally this morning in Niamey and 
airport traffic was normal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

